==English==

===Verb===
{{en-verb|hangs on|hanging on|hung on}}

# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} To [[wait]] a [[moment]] (usually imperative).
#: {{ux|en|'''Hang on'''. Let me check.}}
# To [[hold]], [[grasp]], or [[grip]].
#: {{ux|en|'''Hang on''' to the handle so you don't drop it.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1913|author={{w|Joseph C. Lincoln}}|chapter=7
|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL5535161W Mr. Pratt's Patients]
|passage=Old Applegate, in the stern, just set and looked at me, and Lord James, amidship, waved both arms and kept hollering for help. I took a couple of everlasting big strokes and managed to grab hold of the skiff's rail, close to the stern. Then, for a jiffy, I '''hung on''' and fought for breath.}}
# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} To keep; to store something for someone
#: {{ux|en|'''Hang on''' to my jacket until I get back.}}
# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} To pay close [[attention]].
#: {{ux|en|The audience '''hangs on''' his every word.}}
# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} To continually [[believe]] in something; to have [[faith]] in.
#: {{ux|en|He's got a philosophy he '''hangs on''' to.}}
# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} To [[persevere]].
#: {{ux|en|Just '''hang on''' and keep going; this pain won't last forever.}}
#* '''1972''' : ''Perfect Day'' by [[w:Lou Reed|Lou Reed]]
#*: It's such a perfect day, I'm glad I spend it with you
#*: Such a perfect day you just keep me '''hanging on'''
#*: You just keep me '''hanging on'''

